# Domain Layer Is Mandatory - Never Empty

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

This rule has no exceptions. There is no scenario - not a "simple" entity,
not a CRUD-only feature, not time pressure - that permits leaving the domain
layer empty or skipping domain types and errors.

Prohibited judgement calls:
- "This entity is simple CRUD with no logic, I'll skip the domain file." - No. Create the interface and a domain error. Even thin domain models must exist.
- "I'll put the business rule in the repository for now." - No. Business rules belong in domain. Repositories are infrastructure - they persist and fetch. They must not own logic.
- "The DTO is close enough to the domain entity, I'll use it instead." - No. DTOs carry joined/presentation data. Domain entities carry only the entity's own properties. They are not the same type.
- "I'll come back and populate domain later." - No. Domain is written first, before the repository, before the use case.
- "There's no logic yet, so there's nothing to put in domain." - No. The interface type itself belongs in domain even if there are no rules today.

---

## What belongs in the domain layer

### Entity interfaces

Every entity in the application has a corresponding interface in
`src/main/domain/[entity].ts`. The interface carries only the entity's own
persistent properties - no joined fields, no display-only fields.

```typescript
// CORRECT - domain entity owns its own data only
export interface Task {
  readonly id: string
  readonly title: string
  readonly status: TaskStatus
  readonly projectId: string   // foreign key - NOT projectName
  readonly staffId: string | null   // foreign key - NOT staffName
  // ... other own properties
}

// WRONG - domain entity should not contain joined display data
export interface Task {
  readonly projectName: string  // this belongs in a DTO, not the domain entity
  readonly staffName: string | null  // same
}
```

### Domain errors

Every entity has at least one domain error for "not found." Additional errors
cover each invariant that can be violated.

```typescript
// src/main/domain/errors.ts
export class TaskNotFoundError extends Error {
  constructor(id: string) {
    super(`Task not found: ${id}`)
    this.name = 'TaskNotFoundError'
  }
}
```

Repositories MUST throw typed domain errors, never raw `Error` instances:

```typescript
// WRONG - raw Error in infrastructure
throw new Error(`Task record not found: ${id}`)

// CORRECT - typed domain error
import { TaskNotFoundError } from '../../domain/errors'
throw new TaskNotFoundError(id)
```

### Business rule functions

Any rule that governs how an entity changes state belongs in `domain/` as a
pure function. This includes:

- Setting `closedAt` when a task transitions to Complete
- Deriving defaults (initials from name, status defaults)
- Validation rules (name must not be empty)
- Any condition that controls a state transition

```typescript
// CORRECT - domain function owns the closedAt rule
// src/main/domain/task.ts
export function resolveClosedAt(
  newStatus: TaskStatus,
  currentClosedAt: string | null,
  now: string
): string | null {
  return newStatus === 'Complete' ? now : currentClosedAt
}
```

---

## What does NOT belong in the domain layer

- Database queries or ORM calls - those are infrastructure
- HTTP calls or IPC calls - those are infrastructure/presentation
- DTO construction with joined data - that is an infrastructure/use-case concern
- React components or hooks - those are renderer

---

## File structure for a new entity

When adding entity `Foo`, create these domain files before writing any other layer:

```
src/main/domain/foo.ts      - Foo interface + business rule functions
src/main/domain/errors.ts   - add FooNotFoundError (and other Foo errors)
src/main/domain/index.ts    - re-export Foo and its errors
```

---

## The cost of skipping this

When business rules live in repositories:
- The same rule must be tested through a database fixture (expensive, slow)
- The rule cannot be tested in isolation without spinning up infrastructure
- The rule is invisible to the application layer and cannot be reused
- Future developers cannot find where the rule lives

When domain types do not exist:
- Use cases and ports must reference DTOs (presentation objects) as their
  primary domain model, which conflates two concerns that must be separate
- There is no single authoritative definition of what the entity IS

